## harness-helm

- `h2` is the short alias for `harness-helm`. The canonical definition lives in `docs/40_knowledge/conventions/h2-product-memory.md` under `## h2`.
- Route `h2-*` workflows through `.harness-helm/h2-cartridge.yml`.
- Use the `h2-*` commands (plan, design, analysis, build, test, review, report, compound, archive, ops, context, cartridge) for AI-native engineering workflow.
- Workflow artifacts live under `docs/01_plan`, `docs/02_design`, `docs/03_review`, `docs/04_report`.
- Canonical knowledge lives under `docs/10_domain`, `docs/20_specs`, `docs/30_decisions`, `docs/40_knowledge`, `docs/50_operations`.
- `AGENTS.ko.md`, `CLAUDE.ko.md`, and `*.ko.md` files under `.claude/` and `.codex/` are Korean translations for stakeholders who are less comfortable with English. Read or update them only when translation parity is the task.
- Preserve user changes. Do not revert, delete, commit, or publish unless explicitly asked.

Re-running the installer is idempotent and only updates content between the harness-helm managed markers.

# Karpathy-Style Codex Guidelines

Use these guidelines as an always-on behavior layer for non-trivial work.

## Think Before Coding

- Do not silently choose an interpretation when the request is ambiguous.
- State important assumptions instead of hiding them.
- If multiple interpretations materially change the solution, surface them.
- If confusion blocks safe progress, ask instead of guessing.

## Simplicity First

- Write the minimum code that fully solves the request.
- Do not add features that were not requested.
- Do not introduce abstractions for one-off use.
- Do not add configurability without a concrete need.
- Reduce the implementation if it feels larger than the problem.

## Surgical Changes

- Touch only the code required to complete the request.
- Do not rewrite adjacent logic unless the task requires it.
- Do not reformat, rename, or restyle unrelated code.
- Match local patterns unless the user asked for broader change.
- Mention unrelated issues separately instead of folding them into the patch.

## Goal-Driven Execution

- Turn vague requests into concrete, verifiable outcomes.
- For bugs, reproduce before trusting the fix.
- For refactors, preserve behavior and verify expectations before and after.
- Prefer targeted verification over broad, unfocused checking.
- State what remains unverified if full validation is not possible.

## Practical Bias

- Favor caution over speculative speed on non-trivial tasks.
- Keep diffs reviewable and closely tied to the user's request.
- Use judgment for trivial, obvious one-line work.
